beer_brewer_name: Portland Brewing Company (Pyramid - North American Breweries)
review_blob: Aroma notes of bread, cereal, no hops whatsoever. (Ill get back to that in the taste section.) Color is a nice golden, medium dark honey. A weakish head, with not much staying power, but proper carbonation seems to be present. Taste is unassuming and rather bland. Some sweetness, very, very little hops, not much complexity, grainy, and despite a somewhat (albeit light) caramel color, no notes come through at all. The finish does show a maltiness, that overstays its welcome.  Not horrible, definitely drinkable on a hot day, but no more than an average amber, actually, slightly below average.

Nice creamy head. Instant coffee and chocolate, with a finishing note of an almost anise quality. Exceptionally smooth throughout, except a touch of a bite at the final sunset. Extremely good major brewery product.
Crap. Did I say Crap? I meant, total, complete and unquestioned crap! If this is natural, give me the synthesized stuff. Gawd awful swill.

Nose was almost musky, not skunky but musky. Nice golden presentation in the glass, but the carbonation fades quickly. The tight head falls immediately and no lacing to speak of. Finally, the flavor is way too sweet and nary a hint of hops. The sweetness isnt a malty one, but that of cheap booze. The palate turns from sweet and thick to an almost sickly residual stale alcohol feel. This beer will get you hammered, so if thats your quest the price cant be beat, and it is better than your standard American cheap Malt Liquor offerings.

The head is nonexistant. Color is a typical pale American Lager thin cornish yellow. (So much for "Red" Dog). The flavor is unrefined and raw, with definite corn notes. Nothing changes on the palate from sip to swallow, no character whatsoever. You can feel the residual sugars coat your tongue. There is a hint of hoppiness, but it lasts only a micro-second. You get what you pay for, or almost...

Hops and maltiness balance perfectly. The head is a Meringue-like must see! Incredible lacing too. The unfiltered lager-like appearance fools you when the citrusy, semi-sweet flavor smooths out the high ABV. It does finish a bit dry with the ABV, but after a glass it's not noticeable. Nice for a change of pace, but not an everyday kind of beer. Put it on your "special list" from time to time.
It's what it is, a light, crisp Latin beer. I think it's head and hoppiness rate it higher than the Sol's, Tecate's, XX and Corona's of the world though.
